{"status":"success","result":"The silent evaluator concept is exactly right — and it's stronger than user feedback alone because it fires on every interaction, not just flagged ones.\n\n*Two distinct signals the coordinator can generate silently:*\n\n• *Draft accuracy* — already implicit in the code. If `secretaryDraft` was set and the coordinator's response closely matches it, the draft was good. If the coordinator overrode significantly, the draft failed. String similarity between draft and final response gives you this without an extra LLM call.\n\n• *Routing accuracy* — did the assigned tier handle it, or did it escalate? An escalation event is a direct routing failure signal. No extra call needed — it's already logged.\n\nBoth signals can be written to a `routing-feedback.jsonl` with the original message, the classification decision, and the grade. Every N entries, distill into updated few-shot examples and prepend to the classify prompt. The Secretary gets smarter without any human intervention.\n\n*The architectural thing to nail:* these are two separate quality dimensions. A draft can be routed correctly but worded badly. A draft can be perfectly worded but sent to the wrong model tier. They should be tracked separately so the Secretary improves on the right axis.\n\n*On the three gaps Claude CLI identified:*\n\nWeb access has the highest user-facing impact but requires infrastructure (search API or headless browser). Proactive memory is the opposite — pure behaviour change, low cost, and it compounds. Every session where Jarvis learns something about DJ makes the next session better. I'd pull memory first because it accelerates everything else, including the feedback loop.\n\nWeb access second. Richer task coverage third — it's incremental and can happen in parallel.\n\nWhat's the current trigger for Jarvis writing to `jarvis.md`? Is it entirely self-initiated, or is there a prompt nudge?","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
